
    SASSA has rubbished claims that people won’t receive their grants in January next year.In a statement released to the media, SASSA denied that their offices will be closed.This was after unconfirmed rumours have been circulating that their offices will be closed next year.if(typeof za24_DisplayAd != "undefined") za24_DisplayAd("300x250","2");<a href="http://pubads.g.doubleclick.net/gampad/jump?iu=/8900/24.com/Web/DailySun/News/National_Article&sz=300x250&c=460919402&t=artid%3d97ff857d-3aa2-4763-a165-b3a23ccb0c37%26accreditation%3ddaily+sun%26posno%3d2" target="_blank"><img src="http://pubads.g.doubleclick.net/gampad/ad?iu=/8900/24.com/Web/DailySun/News/National_Article&sz=300x250&c=460919402&t=artid%3d97ff857d-3aa2-4763-a165-b3a23ccb0c37%26accreditation%3ddaily+sun%26posno%3d2" border="0" alt=""></a>It also said that their offices will only close on public holidays.“We urge our beneficiaries to report such acts of criminality to the police so that these scammers can be put behind bars,” the statement said.“Social grant payments for December were currently being made and the process will continue until December 15 at pay-points.“Beneficiaries who receive their grants at ATMs and shops can do so until December 22,” it also said.As from January 2018, grant payments will be paid as per usual, on the first day of every month.SASSA’s acting CEO, Pearl Bhengu, issued a warning to grant recepients.“Remain vigilant and never disclose your card details, including pin or ID Numbers,” she said.“I also want to take this opportunity to wish all beneficiaries of social grants a safe and happy festive season,” she added.
